public interface NativeCapable

The NativeCapable is the interface implemented by all native capable classes.

An object of a class implementing this interface is a "native capable object". This object can be made native using makeNative() and attach() methods of NativeManager or used as parameter of methods defined as native or set in fields of other native objects. A native object has an address and occupies some native memory; this native memory is accessible from native world and is synchronized automatically with Java data elements when these elements are accessed.

There are two types of NativeCapable based classes: predefined/internal of the framework (using the related interfaces) and user defined native capable classes previously enhanced (on filesystem or when loading).

Author:
Jose M. Arranz Santamaria

Method Detail

jnieasyGetNativeStateManager

NativeStateManager jnieasyGetNativeStateManager()
Returns the native state manager instance that controls this native capable object instance.

If the returned reference is not null, the object is native, else is non-native.

Returns:
the state manager instance of this object if native, else null.
See Also:
NativeStateManager.getNativeCapable()

jnieasyGetType

TypeNative jnieasyGetType()
Returns the type declaration used in this object.

If the object is an instance of a user defined native class, and this method is called immediately after the instance creation with a normal new sentence, the returned type is the default type of the user defined class.

If the object was created using a TypeNative object like TypeNativeObject.newValue(), the returned object is this TypeNative object.

The original type is not ever respected: if this instance is referenced by a native field "by value", the returned type object is the type of the field declaration.

Returns:
the type declaration of this object.
See Also:
NativeClassDescriptor.getType()
